description: This succulent was small, and its leaves were green and thin. This is the main dudleya species of the Yosemite region. It was such an awesome jewel on the vertical, mossy slope overlooking the Lower Montane Forest.

This manzanita species is also abundant in the Sierras. The leaves are large, gray/green ovals. The stems were slick, red, and woody. The flowers were soft whites and pinks. This grew near the rocks in the Lower Montane Forest.
The plant was small and stayed near the ground. It had many sprouted leaves with a small, fuzzy, fern-like structure. It was nestled between the grass and leaf litter of the Lower Montane Forest.
The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. The bark was flaky, grooved, and dark orange/brown. It was a youngster, growing in the shadows of the larger conifers of the Lower Montane Forest.

The tree was winter deciduous, with its buds being the only signs of life on the tree. The small green flowers were in abundance, cradled by four "petals". This structure of the flowers is that of the dogwoods, and this is the main species in the Lower Montane Forests of the Sierras.
The tree was an evergreen with gray, sprawling branches. The leaves were shiny, smooth, and had fragrance to them. It grew along the large granite boulders of the Lower Montane Forest.

Based on its lack of malleation, strong striations, yellowish-umber coloration, and location, I agree with @pliffgrieff that this is very likely H. t. grippi. In all of these features it matches the description given in Pilsbry's monograph on the North American terrestrial mollusks.
Thanks to @finatic for helping point this snail out to me. Based on the maculations on the shell and its rich coloration I believe this is H. tudiculata.
